1. Introduction and Motivation

The prospect of sustained human presence on Mars hinges critically on the ability to produce propellant from local resources—a practice known as In-Situ Resource Utilization (ISRU). The Sabatier reaction,

\mathrm{CO_2 + 4H_2 \rightleftharpoons CH_4 + 2H_2O} \quad (\Delta H^\circ = -165\ \mathrm{kJ/mol}),

offers a direct pathway to synthesize methane (CH₄) from atmospheric carbon dioxide and electrolytic hydrogen. When paired with oxygen produced via water electrolysis or solid-oxide co-electrolysis, this methane-oxygen bipropellant can fuel the Mars Ascent Vehicle (MAV), dramatically reducing the landed mass required for a return mission. NASA's reference architecture for a human Mars mission envisions producing approximately 7 metric tons of methane over 14 months of surface operations, requiring a Sabatier reactor with a production capacity of roughly 0.5–1.0 kg h⁻¹ of CH₄.

Despite the apparent simplicity of the Sabatier chemistry, operating such a reactor on the Martian surface introduces a confluence of extreme environmental and operational challenges that have no terrestrial analogue:

· Low ambient pressure (600 Pa, approximately 0.6% of Earth's sea-level pressure) radically alters gas transport, shifting from continuum Fickian diffusion to Knudsen-dominated flow within catalyst pores.
· Trace contaminants from the Martian atmosphere and from perchlorate-bearing water electrolysis—particularly chlorine species and fine dust—poison catalyst active sites and accelerate deactivation.
· Solar power intermittency imposes hundreds of start-up and shutdown cycles over a mission lifetime, each of which subjects the catalyst to thermal and chemical transients that promote sintering and coking.
· Zero-consumable requirement precludes the use of expendable sorbents or regenerable beds that depend on resupply; the system must operate autonomously for thousands of hours with only periodic in-situ regeneration.

Recent breakthroughs in membrane reactor technology, as reported by Ullah et al. (2025) in Nature Communications, have demonstrated that integrating a water-permselective membrane into a Sabatier reactor can achieve >99% CO₂ conversion and stable operation over 10 days under simulated intermittent power. Concurrently, advances in safe reinforcement learning with Lyapunov constraints (Neto et al., 2025) and in Bayesian optimal experimental design (BOED) for catalyst development (Murphy, 2026) provide the methodological tools to address the autonomy and parameterization challenges unique to the Martian environment.

This thesis synthesizes these recent developments into a unified, mathematically rigorous framework for the design, modeling, and autonomous control of a Mars ISRU Sabatier reactor. The contributions are threefold:

1. A comprehensive multi-physics model that couples Dusty Gas Model transport, extended Langmuir-Hinshelwood-Hougen-Watson kinetics with contaminant inhibition, and spatially resolved deactivation dynamics, benchmarked against the latest experimental literature.
2. A novel catalyst health mapping formalism that quantifies the cumulative effects of coking, sintering, and chlorine poisoning in a single scalar field, enabling real-time state estimation and predictive maintenance.
3. A Lyapunov-constrained safe reinforcement learning controller that guarantees closed-loop stability and safety while autonomously managing reactor operation across power cycles and fault scenarios.

The work is structured as a complete research proposal, including a detailed five-phase plan culminating in a 500-hour integrated demonstration at TRL 5–6. All mathematical derivations are presented in full, and critical assumptions are examined in a dedicated synthesis chapter.

