2. Critical Analysis of Prior Work and Identified Research Gaps

Before presenting the proposed framework, it is essential to situate this work within the existing literature and to articulate precisely the gaps that remain unaddressed. This section synthesizes the critical advice and observations accumulated during the development of this thesis.

2.1 The State of the Art in Mars Sabatier Reactors

The Sabatier reaction has been employed in closed-loop life support systems aboard the International Space Station (ISS) for decades, albeit at near-atmospheric pressure and with continuous power. The NASA Kennedy Space Center (KSC) ISRU team has conducted extensive testing of Sabatier reactors at Martian pressures, demonstrating near-equilibrium conversion with ruthenium- and nickel-based catalysts (NASA TechPort, 2025). However, these tests have primarily been steady-state in nature and have not systematically addressed the combined effects of intermittent power, dust contamination, and chlorine poisoning over mission-relevant durations.

A pivotal advancement was reported by Ullah et al. (2025), who integrated a NaA zeolite membrane into a fixed-bed Sabatier reactor. Their system achieved a methane space-time yield of 1947 mmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with zero deactivation over 10 days of continuous operation, and importantly, demonstrated robustness under intermittent power supplies. This work establishes the membrane reactor architecture as the baseline for high-performance Martian Sabatier systems. However, the Ullah study was conducted at laboratory scale and did not incorporate the full suite of Martian stressors—most notably dust loading and chlorine contamination—nor did it address long-term deactivation beyond the 10-day window.

2.2 Transport Modeling at Low Pressure: The Dusty Gas Model Necessity

A recurring theme in the critical review of earlier versions of this work was the necessity of employing the Dusty Gas Model (DGM) rather than Fickian diffusion for transport at 600 Pa. The Knudsen number, defined as the ratio of the molecular mean free path to the characteristic pore diameter,

Kn = \frac{\lambda}{d_p},

exceeds 0.1 for typical catalyst pore sizes (10–50 nm) at Martian pressure. Under these conditions, molecule-wall collisions dominate over molecule-molecule collisions, and Fick's law fails to capture the coupling between species fluxes and the pressure-driven viscous flow. The DGM, derived from the Boltzmann equation with a momentum sink term representing the porous medium, unifies Knudsen diffusion, molecular diffusion, and Darcy flow into a single flux framework. This formulation is critical because pressure drops across a 1-meter catalyst bed can exceed 10–20% of the total Martian pressure—a phenomenon that standard Fickian models cannot resolve.

2.3 Catalyst Deactivation Mechanisms: Coking, Sintering, and Poisoning

Heterogeneous catalyst deactivation is conventionally classified into three primary mechanisms: poisoning (strong chemisorption of impurities), coking (carbon deposition blocking active sites), and sintering (loss of active surface area due to crystallite growth). In the Martian context, an additional mechanism emerges: chlorine poisoning from perchlorate electrolysis. The chlorine species (HCl, Cl₂) adsorb strongly on nickel and ruthenium surfaces, competing with CO₂ and H₂ for active sites and accelerating coking rates.

The critical review identified a subtle but important error in earlier formulations of the regeneration kinetics. A regeneration term of the form

\frac{\partial a_{\text{recover}}}{\partial t} = k_{\text{reg}}(T) \, C_{\text{coke}} \, a

is physically inconsistent, as it implies that the recovery rate increases with coke concentration even as coke is removed. The corrected formulation separates deactivation and recovery, with regeneration driven by hydrogen partial pressure and the fraction of reversible coke:

\frac{\partial a}{\partial t} = -k_d(T, \theta_{\text{Cl}}) \, a \, C_{\text{coke}} + k_{\text{reg}}(T) \, P_{\text{H}_2} \, (1 - a) \, \theta_{\text{coke,reversible}}.

This ensures that recovery asymptotically approaches full activity as coke is removed and ceases when hydrogen is absent.

2.4 The Lyapunov Stability Sign Error and Its Correction

A significant issue identified in the mathematical appendix of Version 6.0 was a sign error in the Lyapunov stability proof. The earlier formulation defined L(s) = -V(s) and required \dot{L}(s) \leq 0, which implies \dot{V}(s) \geq 0—the opposite of stability. This error undermined the formal safety guarantee that constitutes a key contribution of the thesis.

The corrected framework separates stability (convergence to the setpoint) from safety (remaining within operational bounds) using a Control Lyapunov Function (CLF) and a Control Barrier Function (CBF), respectively. The CLF condition,

\dot{V}(\mathbf{s}) = \frac{\partial V}{\partial \mathbf{s}} \cdot f(\mathbf{s}, \mathbf{a}) \leq -\alpha V(\mathbf{s}), \quad \alpha > 0,

guarantees exponential convergence to the desired production state. The CBF condition,

\dot{h}(\mathbf{s}) + \gamma h(\mathbf{s}) \geq 0, \quad \gamma > 0,

guarantees forward invariance of the safe set \mathcal{C} = \{\mathbf{s} \mid h(\mathbf{s}) \geq 0\}. The reinforcement learning policy is constrained to satisfy both conditions, providing formal guarantees of both stability and safety.

2.5 PINN Convergence and Lipschitz Continuity

The Physics-Informed Neural Network (PINN) surrogate is proposed as a computationally efficient replacement for online CFD solves. An earlier version of the thesis claimed a rigorous error bound of the form

\|\mathbf{u} - \mathbf{u}_{\text{PINN}}\|_{L^2} \leq C_1 \sqrt{\mathcal{L}_{\text{PDE}}} + C_2 \sqrt{\mathcal{L}_{\text{data}}},

citing Lipschitz continuity of the PDE operator as a sufficient condition. The critical review noted that Lipschitz continuity of the DGM operator coupled with nonlinear LHHW kinetics has not been proven. The corrected text presents this bound as a heuristic estimate—a practical diagnostic for training convergence—rather than a formal theorem.

2.6 BOED Parameter Identifiability and the Chlorine-Coking Interaction

The Bayesian Optimal Experimental Design (BOED) framework is proposed to efficiently parameterize the kinetic and deactivation models. However, the interaction between chlorine poisoning and coking rate—modeled via the term \theta_{\text{Cl}} \times C_{\text{coke}}—is expected to exhibit strong correlation, limiting identifiability even with accelerated aging data. The BOED acquisition function is therefore augmented with a penalty on expected posterior variance to prioritize experiments that decorrelate these parameters. The final Gaussian Process surrogate will report appropriately widened confidence intervals for predictions involving simultaneous high chlorine and high coke concentrations.

2.7 Engineering Details: Spacer, Dead-Bus Recovery, and Knudsen Selectivity

Several critical engineering observations emerged during the review process:

· Ru/Ni Interface Management: The graded bed transitions from Ru/Al₂O₃ (fast kinetics, chlorine tolerance) to Ni-CeO₂-ZrO₂ (coking resistance, high selectivity). Under thermal cycling, ruthenium can migrate and alloy with nickel, degrading both phases. A 3 cm inert SiC spacer zone is inserted to prevent interdiffusion.
· Dead-Bus Recovery Protocol: If the reactor loses power during a dust storm and cools to ambient Martian temperature (~210 K), water vapor within the pores will freeze. Upon power restoration, immediate heating could melt this ice, forming liquid water that accelerates hydrothermal sintering of nickel crystallites. The recovery protocol first purges with cold, dry CO₂ to sublimate ice before heating begins.
· Membrane Selectivity at Low Pressure: At 600 Pa feed pressure, Knudsen diffusion across the porous membrane support reduces the effective H₂O/H₂ selectivity by a factor of \sqrt{M_{\text{H}_2}/M_{\text{H}_2O}} \approx 1/3. This correction is incorporated into the membrane flux boundary condition.
· ESP Power and Stability: Operating an electrostatic precipitator in 600 Pa CO₂ requires precise voltage control to maintain stable Trichel pulses within the narrow window between corona onset and sparkover. The AI controller monitors corona current and adjusts electrode spacing to maintain optimal dust collection.

These observations, integrated into the system architecture, significantly enhance the flight readiness of the proposed design.

