8. High-Fidelity Computational Fluid Dynamics Modeling

8.1 Model Scope and Geometry

A 2D axisymmetric CFD model of the membrane-augmented fixed-bed reactor is implemented in OpenFOAM. The computational domain includes:

· Catalyst bed (Ru/Al₂O₃ inlet zone, SiC spacer, Ni-CeO₂-ZrO₂ outlet zone).
· Membrane tubes (porous wall boundary condition with permeance model).
· Inlet plenum and outlet collection volume.

8.2 Numerical Methods

The governing equations are discretized using the finite volume method. The DGM fluxes are computed using a coupled implicit solver to handle the strong coupling between species equations. The pressure-velocity coupling is resolved via the SIMPLE algorithm. Deactivation ODEs are integrated locally at each cell using a stiff ODE solver (CVODE) coupled to the flow solver via operator splitting.

8.3 Benchmarking Protocol

All CFD models are benchmarked against:

1. Experimental data from the Ullah et al. (2025) membrane Sabatier study.
2. NASA KSC Sabatier test data at 600 Pa (NASA TechPort, 2025).
3. Recent (2022–2025) shell-and-tube reactor studies of carbon deposition and thermal degradation.

Validation metrics include:

· Outlet conversion: Mean absolute error < 2% across all operating conditions.
· Temperature profiles: RMS error < 5 K at all thermocouple locations.
· Pressure drop: Predicted vs. measured within 10%.
· Coke deposition rate: Qualitative agreement in spatial distribution and quantitative agreement within 30%.

8.4 Design of the Graded Bed Transition

The 200 mm transition from Ru/Al₂O₃ to Ni-CeO₂-ZrO₂ is based on preliminary CFD simulations indicating that CO₂ conversion reaches approximately 60–70% at this axial location under nominal operation. At this point, the local H₂O partial pressure is high enough that in-situ membrane removal becomes critical, and the thermal profile has stabilized sufficiently to avoid hot-spot formation in the Ni-based section. A 3 cm SiC spacer prevents intermetallic diffusion between the Ru and Ni phases during thermal transients.

