9. Physics-Informed Neural Network–Gaussian Process Surrogate

9.1 Motivation for Surrogate Modeling

The high-fidelity CFD model, while accurate, is computationally prohibitive for real-time control applications. Each simulation requires minutes to hours on a high-performance cluster, whereas the autonomous controller must make decisions on timescales of seconds. A surrogate model is therefore required to provide fast, accurate predictions of the reactor state from sparse sensor data.

9.2 Hybrid PINN-GP Architecture

The surrogate combines two complementary techniques:

· Physics-Informed Neural Network (PINN): A deep neural network trained to satisfy the governing PDEs (species continuity, energy conservation, DGM transport) on a set of collocation points. The PINN enforces physical consistency and provides a smooth, differentiable approximation of the full state field (temperature, concentrations, activity, health).
· Gaussian Process (GP) Layer: Appended to the PINN output, the GP quantifies the epistemic uncertainty associated with the prediction. This uncertainty arises from sparse sensor placement, model discrepancy, and extrapolation beyond the training data.

9.3 Training and Loss Function

The PINN is trained to minimize a composite loss function:

\mathcal{L}(\boldsymbol{\phi}) = \lambda_{\mathrm{data}} \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{data}} + \lambda_{\mathrm{PDE}} \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{PDE}} + \lambda_{\mathrm{BC}} \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{BC}} + \lambda_{\mathrm{entropy}} \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{entropy}},

where:

· \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{data}} = \frac{1}{N_d}\sum \|\mathbf{u}_{\mathrm{PINN}} - \mathbf{u}_{\mathrm{CFD}}\|^2 enforces agreement with CFD training data.
· \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{PDE}} = \frac{1}{N_c}\sum \|\mathcal{F}(\mathbf{u}_{\mathrm{PINN}})\|^2 enforces the governing equations at collocation points.
· \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{BC}} = \frac{1}{N_b}\sum \|\mathcal{B}(\mathbf{u}_{\mathrm{PINN}})\|^2 enforces boundary conditions.
· \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{entropy}} is the GP marginal likelihood, optimized jointly with the neural network weights.

9.4 Heuristic Error Estimate

Assuming the PDE operator \mathcal{F} is Lipschitz continuous with respect to its arguments in the operational domain, the L^2 approximation error satisfies the empirical bound:

\|\mathbf{u} - \mathbf{u}_{\mathrm{PINN}}\|_{L^2} \leq C_1 \sqrt{\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{PDE}}} + C_2 \sqrt{\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{data}}},

where C_1 and C_2 are constants estimated from a validation dataset. This bound serves as a practical diagnostic for training convergence.

9.5 Inference Latency and Deployment

The PINN acts as a neural representation of the pre-computed CFD solution manifold, not an online PDE solver. A forward pass involves a single evaluation of a 5-layer fully connected network with 256 neurons per layer, achieving <100 ms inference latency on NVIDIA Jetson Orin embedded hardware. The training phase is performed offline using high-performance computing resources.

