10. Lyapunov-Constrained Safe Reinforcement Learning Control

10.1 Problem Formulation

The autonomous control problem is formulated as a Markov Decision Process (MDP) with state space \mathcal{S}, action space \mathcal{A}, transition dynamics p(\mathbf{s}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{s}_t, \mathbf{a}_t), and reward function R(\mathbf{s}_t, \mathbf{a}_t). The state vector includes:

\mathbf{s}_t = [\mathbf{T}_{\mathrm{sensors}}, \Delta P, \mathbf{F}_{\mathrm{inlet}}, \mathbf{y}_{\mathrm{MS}}, \mathcal{H}_{\mathrm{PINN}}, \sigma_{\mathrm{GP}}, P_{\mathrm{forecast}}],

where \mathbf{T}_{\mathrm{sensors}} are the 16 thermocouple readings, \Delta P is the pressure drop, \mathbf{F}_{\mathrm{inlet}} are the feed flow rates, \mathbf{y}_{\mathrm{MS}} is the mass spectrometer composition vector, \mathcal{H}_{\mathrm{PINN}} and \sigma_{\mathrm{GP}} are the PINN-GP health prediction and uncertainty, and P_{\mathrm{forecast}} is the solar power forecast.

The action space, structured as an operation recipe, is:

\mathbf{a}_t = [\mathrm{H_2:CO_2\ ratio}, \mathrm{GHSV}, \mathrm{coolant\ duty\ cycle}].

10.2 Control Lyapunov Function (CLF) for Stability

A scalar function V: \mathcal{S} \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} is a Control Lyapunov Function (CLF) for the reactor system with respect to the setpoint \mathbf{s}^* if V(\mathbf{s}^*) = 0, V(\mathbf{s}) > 0 for \mathbf{s} \neq \mathbf{s}^*, and there exists a control policy such that:

\dot{V}(\mathbf{s}) = \frac{\partial V}{\partial \mathbf{s}} \cdot f(\mathbf{s}, \mathbf{a}) \leq -\alpha V(\mathbf{s}), \quad \alpha > 0.

This condition guarantees exponential convergence of the state to the setpoint.

10.3 Control Barrier Function (CBF) for Safety

A scalar function h: \mathcal{S} \to \mathbb{R} defines a safe set \mathcal{C} = \{\mathbf{s} \mid h(\mathbf{s}) \geq 0\}. h is a Control Barrier Function (CBF) if there exists a policy satisfying:

\dot{h}(\mathbf{s}) + \gamma h(\mathbf{s}) \geq 0, \quad \gamma > 0.

This condition guarantees forward invariance of the safe set: if the system starts in \mathcal{C}, it remains in \mathcal{C} for all future time.

10.4 Safe Reinforcement Learning Policy

We employ a Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) agent with Lyapunov and barrier constraints. The reward function incorporates penalties for safety violations and Lyapunov constraint violations:

R(\mathbf{s}_t, \mathbf{a}_t) = \eta_{\mathrm{CH_4}} - \lambda_1 C_{\mathrm{coke}} - \lambda_2 P_{\mathrm{grid}} - \lambda_3 \sigma_{\mathrm{GP}} - \lambda_4 \max(0, -\dot{h} - \gamma h) - \lambda_5 \max(0, \dot{V} + \alpha V).

The PPO policy is trained in a simulation environment that includes the PINN-GP surrogate as the plant model. Domain randomization and physics-based noise injection ensure robust sim-to-real transfer.

10.5 Dead-Bus Recovery and Start-Up/Shutdown Protocols

The policy includes explicit logic for handling power loss events. Upon restoration of power after a cold soak, the controller initiates a low-power recovery sequence:

1. Purge with cold, dry CO₂ (from the atmospheric compressor) to sublimate any ice within the catalyst pores.
2. Once bed temperature exceeds 273 K, commence normal heating ramp.
3. Transition to nominal operation once temperature and composition stabilize.

This protocol prevents the formation of liquid water that would otherwise accelerate hydrothermal sintering of nickel crystallites.

