Appendix A: Thermodynamics and Equilibrium at Martian Conditions

A.1 Standard Gibbs Free Energy and Equilibrium Constant

The Sabatier reaction is:

\mathrm{CO_2 + 4H_2 \rightleftharpoons CH_4 + 2H_2O} \quad (\Delta H^\circ_{298} = -165\ \mathrm{kJ/mol})

The standard Gibbs free energy change at temperature T is:

\Delta G^\circ(T) = \Delta H^\circ(T) - T\Delta S^\circ(T)

Using standard thermochemical data (Vargaftik, 1975; NIST Chemistry WebBook):

Species \Delta H_f^\circ (kJ/mol) S^\circ (J/mol·K)
CO₂ -393.5 213.8
H₂ 0 130.7
CH₄ -74.9 186.3
H₂O(g) -241.8 188.8

Reaction enthalpy:

\Delta H^\circ = (-74.9) + 2(-241.8) - [(-393.5) + 4(0)] = -165.0\ \mathrm{kJ/mol}

Reaction entropy:

\Delta S^\circ = 186.3 + 2(188.8) - [213.8 + 4(130.7)] = -172.4\ \mathrm{J/(mol \cdot K)}

Temperature-dependent Gibbs free energy (assuming constant \Delta H^\circ and \Delta S^\circ over the operating range 200–450 °C):

\Delta G^\circ(T) = -165000 + 172.4\,T \quad (\mathrm{J/mol})

The equilibrium constant in terms of partial pressures, referenced to standard state P^\circ = 1\ \mathrm{bar} = 10^5\ \mathrm{Pa}, is:

K_p(T) = \exp\left(-\frac{\Delta G^\circ(T)}{RT}\right) = \exp\left(\frac{165000}{RT} - \frac{172.4}{R}\right)

With R = 8.314\ \mathrm{J/(mol \cdot K)}:

\frac{172.4}{8.314} \approx 20.73

Thus:

K_p(T) = \exp\left(\frac{165000}{RT} - 20.73\right)

Note: Some literature uses an approximate value of 32.8 for the constant term, which corresponds to a different reference state or includes heat capacity corrections. We adopt the thermochemically consistent value of 20.73.

A.2 Equilibrium Calculation at 573 K (300 °C)

At T = 573\ \mathrm{K}:

\frac{165000}{8.314 \times 573} = \frac{165000}{4763.9} \approx 34.63

K_p(573) = \exp(34.63 - 20.73) = \exp(13.90) \approx 1.09 \times 10^6

This large equilibrium constant indicates that the reaction is strongly product-favored at 300 °C. However, K_p is defined in terms of dimensionless partial pressures (p_i / P^\circ). At Martian total pressure P_{\text{total}} = 600\ \mathrm{Pa} = 0.006\ P^\circ, the actual equilibrium conversion must account for the pressure dependence.

A.3 Pressure Dependence and Equilibrium Conversion

The equilibrium relation for a stoichiometric feed (H₂:CO₂ = 4:1, inert-free) is:

K_p = \frac{(p_{\mathrm{CH_4}}/P^\circ)(p_{\mathrm{H_2O}}/P^\circ)^2}{(p_{\mathrm{CO_2}}/P^\circ)(p_{\mathrm{H_2}}/P^\circ)^4} = \frac{y_{\mathrm{CH_4}} y_{\mathrm{H_2O}}^2}{y_{\mathrm{CO_2}} y_{\mathrm{H_2}}^4} \left(\frac{P_{\text{total}}}{P^\circ}\right)^{-2}

Let X be the fractional conversion of CO₂. For a stoichiometric feed with 1 mole CO₂ and 4 moles H₂ initially:

Species Initial Change Final Mole Fraction
CO₂ 1 -X 1-X (1-X)/(5-2X)
H₂ 4 -4X 4(1-X) 4(1-X)/(5-2X)
CH₄ 0 +X X X/(5-2X)
H₂O 0 +2X 2X 2X/(5-2X)
Total 5  5-2X 1

Substituting into the equilibrium expression:

K_p = \frac{X (2X)^2}{(1-X) [4(1-X)]^4} \cdot \frac{(5-2X)^2}{(5-2X)^4} \cdot \left(\frac{P_{\text{total}}}{P^\circ}\right)^{-2}

Simplifying:

K_p = \frac{4X^3}{(1-X)^5 \cdot 256} \cdot (5-2X)^{-2} \cdot \left(\frac{P^\circ}{P_{\text{total}}}\right)^2

K_p = \frac{X^3}{64 (1-X)^5 (5-2X)^2} \left(\frac{P^\circ}{P_{\text{total}}}\right)^2

For P_{\text{total}} = 600\ \mathrm{Pa} and P^\circ = 10^5\ \mathrm{Pa}:

\frac{P^\circ}{P_{\text{total}}} = \frac{10^5}{600} \approx 166.7

\left(\frac{P^\circ}{P_{\text{total}}}\right)^2 \approx 27778

Thus:

K_p \approx \frac{X^3}{64 (1-X)^5 (5-2X)^2} \times 27778

At 573 K, K_p \approx 1.09 \times 10^6. Solving numerically yields X \approx 0.9997, confirming >99% equilibrium conversion at Martian pressure.

A.4 Reverse Water-Gas Shift (RWGS) Equilibrium

The RWGS reaction:

\mathrm{CO_2 + H_2 \rightleftharpoons CO + H_2O} \quad (\Delta H^\circ = +41\ \mathrm{kJ/mol})

Standard thermodynamic data:

Species \Delta H_f^\circ (kJ/mol) S^\circ (J/mol·K)
CO -110.5 197.7

Reaction enthalpy:

\Delta H^\circ_{\text{RWGS}} = (-110.5) + (-241.8) - [(-393.5) + 0] = +41.2\ \mathrm{kJ/mol}

Reaction entropy:

\Delta S^\circ_{\text{RWGS}} = 197.7 + 188.8 - [213.8 + 130.7] = +42.0\ \mathrm{J/(mol \cdot K)}

Gibbs free energy:

\Delta G^\circ_{\text{RWGS}}(T) = 41200 - 42.0\,T \quad (\mathrm{J/mol})

Equilibrium constant:

K_{p,\text{RWGS}}(T) = \exp\left(-\frac{41200}{RT} + \frac{42.0}{R}\right) = \exp\left(-\frac{41200}{RT} + 5.05\right)

At 573 K:

K_{p,\text{RWGS}}(573) = \exp\left(-\frac{41200}{4763.9} + 5.05\right) = \exp(-8.65 + 5.05) = \exp(-3.60) \approx 0.027

This small value indicates that CO formation is thermodynamically limited at 300 °C, but kinetic factors and local temperature excursions can still produce significant CO.

