Appendix C: Catalyst Deactivation and Regeneration Kinetics

C.1 Coking Deactivation

Carbon deposition occurs via two primary routes:

· CO disproportionation (Boudouard): 2\mathrm{CO} \rightarrow \mathrm{C} + \mathrm{CO_2}
· Methane decomposition: \mathrm{CH_4} \rightarrow \mathrm{C} + 2\mathrm{H_2}

At Sabatier conditions, CO disproportionation is the dominant coking mechanism. The rate of coke formation is:

r_{\mathrm{coke}} = k_c(T) \, P_{\mathrm{CO}}^m \, (1 - \theta_{\mathrm{coke}})^n

where \theta_{\mathrm{coke}} is the fractional coverage of carbon on the surface.

The deactivation rate is proportional to coke accumulation and the remaining activity:

\frac{\partial a}{\partial t} = -k_d(T, \theta_{\mathrm{Cl}}) \, a \, C_{\mathrm{coke}}

The deactivation rate constant k_d is enhanced by chlorine, which weakens metal-support interactions and promotes carbon nucleation:

k_d(T, \theta_{\mathrm{Cl}}) = k_{d0} \exp\left(-\frac{E_d}{RT}\right) \cdot (1 + \beta_{\mathrm{Cl}} \theta_{\mathrm{Cl}})

C.2 Sintering Kinetics

Sintering is the loss of active surface area due to crystallite growth. The rate follows a power-law expression (Bartholomew, 2001):

\frac{d(D/D_0)}{dt} = k_{\mathrm{sint}}(T) \left(\frac{D}{D_0}\right)^n

where D is the average crystallite diameter and D_0 is the initial diameter. In terms of surface area S \propto 1/D:

\frac{dS}{dt} = -k_{\mathrm{sint}}(T) \, S^n

The sintering rate constant is highly temperature-sensitive, with an activation energy typically 100–200 kJ/mol. It accelerates dramatically as the temperature approaches the Tammann temperature (≈590 °C for Ni), at which surface atoms become mobile.

We model this enhancement as:

k_{\mathrm{sint}}(T) = k_{\mathrm{sint}}^0 \exp\left(-\frac{E_{\mathrm{sint}}}{RT}\right) \cdot \left[1 + \eta \exp\left(-\frac{E_{\mathrm{Tammann}}}{R}\left(\frac{1}{T} - \frac{1}{T_{\mathrm{Tammann}}}\right)\right)\right]

C.3 Chlorine Poisoning

Chlorine adsorbs strongly on Ni and Ru surfaces, blocking active sites and promoting coking. The coverage \theta_{\mathrm{Cl}} evolves according to:

\frac{d\theta_{\mathrm{Cl}}}{dt} = k_{\mathrm{ads,Cl}} P_{\mathrm{HCl}} (1 - \theta_{\mathrm{Cl}}) - k_{\mathrm{des,Cl}} \theta_{\mathrm{Cl}}

At steady state, the coverage is:

\theta_{\mathrm{Cl}} = \frac{K_{\mathrm{Cl}} P_{\mathrm{HCl}}}{1 + K_{\mathrm{Cl}} P_{\mathrm{HCl}}}

where K_{\mathrm{Cl}} = k_{\mathrm{ads,Cl}} / k_{\mathrm{des,Cl}}.

C.4 Regeneration Kinetics (Corrected)

Regeneration is achieved by periodically switching to a hydrogen-rich feed (H₂:CO₂ = 6:1) at 300–320 °C. Under these conditions, filamentous carbon is gasified via:

\mathrm{C + 2H_2 \rightarrow CH_4}

The regeneration rate is proportional to the hydrogen partial pressure and the amount of gasifiable carbon:

\frac{\partial a_{\mathrm{recover}}}{\partial t} = k_{\mathrm{reg}}(T) \, P_{\mathrm{H_2}} \, (1 - a) \, \theta_{\mathrm{coke,reversible}}

where \theta_{\mathrm{coke,reversible}} is the fraction of deposited carbon that is accessible and reactive (filamentous carbon), as opposed to encapsulating carbon which is inert under mild regeneration conditions.

The net activity evolution is:

\frac{\partial a}{\partial t} = -k_d(T, \theta_{\mathrm{Cl}}) \, a \, C_{\mathrm{coke}} + k_{\mathrm{reg}}(T) \, P_{\mathrm{H_2}} \, (1 - a) \, \theta_{\mathrm{coke,reversible}}

This formulation ensures that:

· Deactivation ceases when coke is absent (C_{\mathrm{coke}} = 0).
· Regeneration ceases when hydrogen is absent (P_{\mathrm{H_2}} = 0) or when activity is fully restored (a = 1).
· Recovery rate is driven by the reactant (H₂) rather than the product (coke).

C.5 Coke Classification and Reversibility

Carbon deposits are classified into three types (Bartholomew, 2001):

Type Structure Reversibility Removal Conditions
Cα Atomic carbon, surface carbide Reversible H₂ at 200–300 °C
Cβ Filamentous/whisker carbon Partially reversible H₂ or O₂ at 300–400 °C
Cγ Encapsulating/graphitic carbon Irreversible under mild conditions O₂ at >500 °C

The fraction \theta_{\mathrm{coke,reversible}} is defined as:

\theta_{\mathrm{coke,reversible}} = \frac{C_{\mathrm{coke,\alpha}} + f_\beta C_{\mathrm{coke,\beta}}}{C_{\mathrm{coke,total}}}

where f_\beta \approx 0.5 accounts for partial reversibility of filamentous carbon. The relative amounts of each coke type are estimated from TPO profiles in literature studies.

