Appendix E: Catalyst Health Mapping — Formal Definition and Weight Calibration

E.1 Definition

The catalyst health metric \mathcal{H}(\mathbf{x},t) \in [0,1] is a spatially resolved scalar field defined as:

\mathcal{H}(\mathbf{x},t) = w_1 a(\mathbf{x},t) + w_2 \left(1 - \frac{S_{\mathrm{loss}}(\mathbf{x},t)}{S_0}\right) - w_3 \theta_{\mathrm{Cl}}(\mathbf{x},t) - w_4 \left(\frac{T(\mathbf{x},t) - T_{\mathrm{safe}}}{\Delta T_{\mathrm{crit}}}\right)^2

with the constraint \sum_{i=1}^4 w_i = 1 and w_i \geq 0.

The terms represent:

· a(\mathbf{x},t): Fractional activity remaining (from deactivation ODE).
· 1 - S_{\mathrm{loss}}/S_0: Fractional surface area remaining (from sintering ODE).
· \theta_{\mathrm{Cl}}: Chlorine coverage penalty.
· Temperature excursion penalty (quadratic, zero at T = T_{\mathrm{safe}}).

E.2 Bayesian Weight Calibration

The weights w_i are calibrated using Bayesian inference on post-mortem characterization data from accelerated aging experiments reported in the literature.

Let \mathbf{w} = [w_1, w_2, w_3, w_4]^T. The prior distribution p(\mathbf{w}) is a Dirichlet distribution (appropriate for simplex-constrained positive weights):

p(\mathbf{w}) = \mathrm{Dirichlet}(\boldsymbol{\alpha}_0)

with \boldsymbol{\alpha}_0 = [2, 2, 1, 1] reflecting a weak prior belief that activity and surface area are more important than poisoning and temperature excursions.

Given a dataset \mathcal{D} = \{(\mathbf{x}_j, \mathcal{H}_j^{\mathrm{obs}})\}_{j=1}^N of observed health metrics from post-mortem analysis (derived from conversion measurements, TEM, XRD, and XPS), the likelihood is:

p(\mathcal{D} \mid \mathbf{w}) = \prod_{j=1}^N \mathcal{N}(\mathcal{H}_j^{\mathrm{obs}} \mid \mathcal{H}(\mathbf{x}_j; \mathbf{w}), \sigma_{\mathrm{obs}}^2)

The posterior is sampled via Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC). The posterior mean weights are used in the online health estimation.

E.3 Bounded Degradation Rate Proposition

Proposition. Under the Lyapunov-constrained policy operating within the CBF-defined safe set, the expected instantaneous rate of catalyst health degradation satisfies:

\mathbb{E}\left[ \frac{d\mathcal{H}}{dt} \right] \geq -\delta_{\mathrm{max}}

where \delta_{\mathrm{max}} > 0 is a constant determined by the maximum allowable temperature T_{\mathrm{max}} and contaminant concentrations.

Proof Sketch. The time derivative of \mathcal{H} is:

\frac{d\mathcal{H}}{dt} = w_1 \frac{\partial a}{\partial t} - w_2 \frac{1}{S_0} \frac{dS}{dt} - w_3 \frac{d\theta_{\mathrm{Cl}}}{dt} - 2w_4 \frac{T - T_{\mathrm{safe}}}{\Delta T_{\mathrm{crit}}^2} \frac{dT}{dt}

Each term is bounded:

· |\partial a / \partial t| \leq k_{d,\max} a C_{\mathrm{coke},\max} (deactivation) and the regeneration term is non-negative.
· |dS/dt| \leq k_{\mathrm{sint}}(T_{\mathrm{max}}) S_0^n (sintering is monotonic and bounded by the rate at T_{\mathrm{max}}).
· |d\theta_{\mathrm{Cl}}/dt| is bounded by the adsorption rate at maximum HCl partial pressure.
· The temperature derivative term is bounded because the CBF constraint limits |dT/dt| within the safe set.

Summing these bounds yields the result. The AI controller minimizes the instantaneous \delta(t) by keeping temperature and contaminants as low as possible while meeting production targets.

