Appendix I: Numerical Methods for CFD and Surrogate Training

I.1 OpenFOAM Solver Customization

The DGM transport equations are implemented in a custom OpenFOAM solver sabatierDGMFoam based on reactingFoam. Key modifications:

· Addition of Knudsen diffusivity calculation.
· Coupled implicit solution of species fluxes using the DGM formulation.
· Operator splitting for deactivation ODEs: at each time step, the flow and reaction fields are advanced, then the ODEs for a, S, and \theta_{\mathrm{Cl}} are integrated using CVODE.
· Membrane boundary condition: a custom membraneFlux boundary condition applies the water removal flux.

I.2 Mesh and Discretization

· 2D axisymmetric wedge mesh with 200 axial × 50 radial cells.
· Second-order upwind for convection, central differencing for diffusion.
· SIMPLE algorithm for pressure-velocity coupling.
· Adaptive time stepping based on CFL condition (max CFL = 0.5).

I.3 PINN Implementation Details

· Framework: PyTorch with automatic differentiation.
· Collocation points: 50,000 interior points + 10,000 boundary points per training case.
· Batch size: 10,000 points.
· Learning rate: 10^{-3} (Adam), 10^{-4} (L-BFGS).
· Activation: Swish (SiLU) for smooth derivatives.
· Weight initialization: Xavier uniform.

I.4 Gaussian Process Layer

The final layer of the PINN outputs the mean \mu(\mathbf{x}) and log-variance \log \sigma^2(\mathbf{x}) of the predictive distribution. The GP kernel is a Matérn 5/2 kernel with automatic relevance determination:

k(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{x}') = \sigma_f^2 \left(1 + \frac{\sqrt{5} r}{\ell} + \frac{5 r^2}{3 \ell^2}\right) \exp\left(-\frac{\sqrt{5} r}{\ell}\right)

where r = \|\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{x}'\|_2 and \ell are learnable lengthscale parameters.

